The '''Malayan black magpie''' ('''''Platysmurus leucopterus''''') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Corvidae]]. Despite its name, it is neither a magpie nor, as was long believed, a jay, but a [[treepie]]. Treepies are a distinct group of corvids externally similar to magpies.<ref name="HBW567">{{Harvnb|dos Anjos|2007|p=567}}</ref>

==Distribution and habitat==
It is found in [[Brunei]], [[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]], [[Myanmar]], [[Singapore]], and [[Thailand]]. The [[Bornean black magpie]] (''P. atterimus'') was formerly considered a subspecies.<ref name="Phillips" /><ref>{{Cite web|title=Species Updates – IOC World Bird List|url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/new/updates/species-updates/|access-date=2021-05-29|language=en-US}}</ref> The natural [[habitat]]s of the Malayan black magpie are [[subtropical or tropical moist lowland forest]] and subtropical or tropical [[mangrove]] forest. It is threatened by [[habitat loss]].

